And the wall collapsed …
<s>Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: 20 years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful one marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
<s>Which one do you remember best and which one had the most significant consequence for the planet?
a) The brutal repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few answered c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarność in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet nothing has contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe – and consequently to the post-war international order reconfiguration.
There will be various commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory from which no one knows the origin.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, we realize that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader of Poland, General Jaruzelski, concluded that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to tackle alone.
Why not appeal to Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of negotiations, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections and Solidarność could participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarność) did not for one moment believe they could lose.
Even in their blackest nightmares, they did not imagine they would be chased from power.
Yet, that is what happened.
In retrospect, it is surprising that there were any doubts.
Solidarity carried out its campaign with brazenness.
A famous poster parodied for the occasion, one from a classic Western film titled "The Train Will Blow Its Whistle Three Times," enjoyed great success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4th was the day of judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughter.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversion that turned into an involuntary self-degradation.
Ils ont conçu un système électoral dans lequel les Polonais, au lieu de sélectionner les candidats de leur choix, devaient barrer les noms de ceux dont ils ne voulaient pas - autant dire tous les communistes qui figuraient sur les bulletins de vote.
Partout où l'on regardait, les gens se débarrassaient des autocrates détestés.
Cela a été enfin le soulèvement populaire que la Pologne attendait de longue date, la revanche sur décembre 1980, lorsque Jaruzelski a décrété la loi martiale, interdit Solidarność et jeté ses dirigeants en prison.
La révolution par le stylo !
Manié avec style, le stylo qui finit par l'emporter sur le sabre, devient l'arme d'une glorieuse vengeance.
Certain voters were tearing up their ballots outright, effectively decapitating the old regime with a swift blow.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"He put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "That apparatchik got rich off our shortage," Pfft!
Pfft!
On the other hand, the communist campaign passed almost unnoticed.
In all Warsaw, only two government candidates took the trouble to put up posters.
The rest relied on the monopoly they had in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
To his credit, the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to declare to them: "Our defeat is total; we need to find a political solution."
This meant that he did not want violence or manipulation; the communists would have to live with the election results.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarity was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The Polish election was extremely encouraging for anticommunists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier became suddenly achievable.
There have been other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously recognized: "We did not see it coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day when freedom burst forth.
